body:
I'm testing an uncontrolled form input via Jest when I confirm the value it's Null (code sample below).

The docs say:

> An `<input>` that does not supply a value (or sets it to null) is an uncontrolled component. In an uncontrolled <input>, the value of the rendered element will reflect the user's input.

The uncontrolled form works as per the docs in the browser but not in Jest.  If I handle the change or use a valueLink the test will pass.

I think it fails here as there is no onChange handler set. 

ReactDomInput.js

``` javascript
_handleChange: function(event) {
    var returnValue;
    var onChange = LinkedValueUtils.getOnChange(this);
    if (onChange) {
      returnValue = onChange.call(this, event);
    }
```

I'm thinking it should throw a warning (if no change handler exists).

My Code / test

Form Input

``` javascript
var MyForm = React.createClass({
  render: function () {
    return (
       <form>
          <input type="text" className="input-email" />
      </form>
    );
  }
});
```

Test

``` javascript
it('Should update value', function() {
    var instance = TestUtils.renderIntoDocument(<MyForm />);
    var el = TestUtils.findRenderedDOMComponentWithClass(instance, 'input-email');
    var node = el.getDOMNode();

    TestUtils.Simulate.change(node,{target: {value: "new value"}});
    expect(node.value).toEqual('new value');
  });

```

Result

```
Using Jest CLI v0.2.2
